.TH GFORK 1 "2026-03-01" "gfork" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
gfork \- isolated git clone workflow for parallel and AI agent development
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B gfork
.I feature-name
.RI [ branch ]
.br
.B gfork cd
.I feature-name
.br
.B gfork rm
.I feature-name
.br
.B gfork ls
.br
.B gfork help
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B gfork
creates an isolated local clone of the current git repository in a sibling
directory.
The clone is named
.IB repo-name -- feature-name
and shares git objects with the original via hardlinks, making it nearly
instant and space-efficient regardless of repo size.
.PP
The clone is fully independent: branches, commits, and working-tree changes
inside it cannot affect the original repository.
When work is complete, push from the clone, pull in the original, then remove
the clone with
.B gfork rm
or
.BR "rm -rf" .
.PP
.B gfork
is especially useful when running multiple AI coding agents in parallel
(Claude Code, Codex, OpenCode, Pi) so each agent works in its own sandbox
without stepping on the others.
.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
.BI "gfork " feature-name " [" branch ]
Create a new clone.
.I feature-name
becomes the suffix of the clone directory
.RI ( repo -- feature-name ).
.I branch
is the branch to clone from; defaults to the current branch when omitted.
Exits non-zero if the destination directory already exists.
.
.TP
.BI "gfork cd " feature-name
Change the current shell directory into an existing clone.
.I feature-name
may be the short feature name
.RI ( auth-refactor )
or the full directory name
.RI ( myrepo--auth-refactor ).
Because this subcommand changes the shell's working directory it must be
implemented as a shell function, not a subprocess.
All supported shells (bash, zsh, fish, nushell) handle this correctly when
installed via the provided installer or shell-specific file.
Exits non-zero if the clone does not exist.
.
.TP
.BI "gfork rm " feature-name
Delete an existing clone after user confirmation.
Before prompting,
.B gfork rm
checks for:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
Uncommitted changes (staged or unstaged) inside the clone.
.IP \(bu 4
Commits that exist in the clone but have not been pushed to a remote.
.RE
.RS
.PP
If either condition is detected a warning is printed above the confirmation
prompt.
Answering
.B y
(case-insensitive) proceeds with deletion; any other input aborts.
.I feature-name
may be the short feature name or the full directory name.
Exits non-zero if the clone does not exist.
.RE
.
.TP
.B gfork ls
List all clones that belong to the current repository.
Clones are detected by scanning the parent directory for siblings whose name
matches the pattern
.IB repo-name -- *.
Each entry is printed with the
.B gfork cd
command needed to jump into it.
Exits non-zero when run outside a git repository.
.
.TP
.BR "gfork update" ", " "gfork upgrade"
Update gfork to the latest version from GitHub.
Downloads the appropriate shell file for the current shell
.RB ( gfork.sh ", " gfork.fish ", or " gfork.nu )
and overwrites the installed copy.
Prints the short commit SHA of the version pulled.
Requires
.BR curl (1)
and an active internet connection.
A shell reload
.RB ( "source ~/.gfork.sh" ", " "exec fish" ", etc.")
is needed to pick up any new subcommands added in the update.
.
.TP
.BR "gfork help" ", " "gfork --help" ", " "gfork -h"
Print a short usage summary and exit.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.B gfork
has no standalone flags.
All behaviour is controlled via subcommands and positional arguments.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (not inside a git repo, destination already exists,
clone not found, missing required argument, etc.).
.B gfork rm
also exits
.B 0
when the user aborts at the confirmation prompt.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic workflow
.EX
# Inside ~/projects/my-app (on branch main)
gfork big-feature          # creates ~/projects/my-app--big-feature
gfork cd big-feature       # jump in
git checkout -b my-branch  # work freely
git push origin my-branch
cd ~/projects/my-app
git pull
gfork rm big-feature       # clean up
.EE
.
.SS Clone a specific branch
.EX
gfork hotfix-login release/v2
gfork cd hotfix-login
.EE
.
.SS List all clones for the current repo
.EX
gfork ls
#   my-app--big-feature   (gfork cd big-feature)
#   my-app--experiment    (gfork cd experiment)
.EE
.
.SS Parallel AI agents
.EX
gfork parallel-sprint
gfork cd parallel-sprint

CLAUDE_CODE_ALLOW_ROOT=1 claude -p "Build the auth module on branch auth" &
CLAUDE_CODE_ALLOW_ROOT=1 claude -p "Build the API layer on branch api"   &
wait

git merge auth
git merge api
git push origin main
cd ~/projects/my-app && git pull
gfork rm parallel-sprint
.EE
.
.SS Per-agent instruction file
.EX
gfork payment-feature
gfork cd payment-feature
cat > AGENTS.md << 'EOF'
Work in an isolated clone. Create one branch per logical unit,
merge back to main when tests pass, never push to origin.
EOF
claude -p "Implement Stripe billing per AGENTS.md"
.EE
.
.SH INSTALLATION
.SS Automatic (detects your shell)
.EX
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/install.sh | bash
.EE
.
.SS Manual
.TP
.B zsh
.EX
mkdir -p ~/.config/zsh/functions
curl -o ~/.config/zsh/functions/gfork.zsh \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.zsh
# Add once to ~/.zshrc:
echo "for f in ~/.config/zsh/functions/*.zsh; source \\$f" >> ~/.zshrc
.EE
.TP
.B bash
.EX
mkdir -p ~/.config/bash/functions
curl -o ~/.config/bash/functions/gfork.bash \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.bash
# Add once to ~/.bashrc:
echo 'for f in ~/.config/bash/functions/*.bash; do source "$f"; done' >> ~/.bashrc
.EE
.TP
.B fish
.EX
curl -o ~/.config/fish/functions/gfork.fish \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.fish
.EE
.TP
.B nushell
.EX
curl -o ~/.config/nushell/gfork.nu \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.nu
echo 'source ~/.config/nushell/gfork.nu' >> ~/.config/nushell/config.nu
.EE
.
.SS Man page
.EX
sudo cp gfork.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/
sudo mandb
man gfork
.EE
.
.SH NOTES
.SS Why not git worktrees?
Git worktrees share the
.I .git
directory with the original repository.
This means the same branch cannot be checked out in two places at once,
and AI agents writing conflicting refs or index entries can corrupt the
original repo.
.B gfork
uses
.B git clone --local
which creates a fully independent
.I .git
directory while still using hardlinks for git object storage, giving
isolation without significant disk overhead.
.
.SS Nushell subcommand names
Nushell does not support subcommands inside a single
.B def
block the same way bash/zsh/fish do.
The nushell version therefore exposes separate top-level commands:
.BR gfork-cd ,
.BR gfork-rm ,
and
.BR gfork-ls
instead of
.BR "gfork cd" ,
.BR "gfork rm" ,
and
.BR "gfork ls" .
.
.SH SHELL SUPPORT
.TS
l l.
bash	gfork.sh
zsh	gfork.sh
fish	gfork.fish
nushell	gfork.nu
.TE
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/zsh/functions/gfork.zsh
Zsh install location. Any
.I *.zsh
file dropped here is loaded automatically when the generic loader line is present in
.IR ~/.zshrc .
.TP
.I ~/.config/bash/functions/gfork.bash
Bash install location. Any
.I *.bash
file dropped here is loaded automatically when the generic loader line is present in
.IR ~/.bashrc .
.TP
.I ~/.config/fish/functions/gfork.fish
Fish auto-load location (no config change needed).
.TP
.I ~/.config/nushell/gfork.nu
Nushell source file (must be sourced from
.IR config.nu ).
.
